# Auth (Supabase Auth)

This project uses **Supabase Auth** for sign in, sign up, password reset, and session management.

## Two Different Clients

Supabase provides separate clients for server and client. Use the correct one for your context.

| Context | Import | Use Case |
|---------|--------|----------|
| Server (RSC, API routes, Server Actions) | `@/lib/supabase/server` | Get current user, validate session, server-side checks |
| Client (browser, Client Components) | `@/lib/supabase/client` | Sign in, sign up, sign out, OAuth flows |

## Server-Side

Use when you need to check auth in Server Components, API routes, or Server Actions.

```ts
import { createServerClient } from "@/lib/supabase/server";

const supabase = createServerClient();
const { data: { user } } = await supabase.auth.getUser();

if (!user) {
  redirect("/login");
}
```

**In a tRPC context (when you add auth):**
```ts
// You might pass user from createTRPCContext
const { data: { user } } = await supabase.auth.getUser();
return { db, user, ... };
```

## Client-Side

Use for login forms, sign up, sign out, and any auth UI.

```ts
import { createBrowserClient } from "@/lib/supabase/client";

const supabase = createBrowserClient();

// Sign in with email/password
const { data, error } = await supabase.auth.signInWithPassword({
  email: "user@example.com",
  password: "password",
});

// Sign out
await supabase.auth.signOut();

// Get current session (reactive)
const { data: { session } } = await supabase.auth.getSession();
```

## Import Paths Summary

- Server: `@/lib/supabase/server` → `createServerClient`
- Client: `@/lib/supabase/client` → `createBrowserClient`

Never use the server client in browser code — it may expose server-only logic or secrets.
